accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Privacy protected and confidential information is restricted from public access for 75 years. Restricted records in this collection have been sealed but not removed from the collection.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Richmond Jaycees, 1936-2002. Accession 37705. Orginization records collection, Library of Virginia, Richmond, Virginia

bioghist.head: Historical Information
bioghist.p: The Richmond Jaycees were founded on May 15, 1936 by a group of fifty men who came together as charters members. The organization was originally known as the Richmond Junior Board o Trade. The group was incorporated September 3, 1940.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Records, 1936-2002, of the Richmond Jaycees, a volunteer, civic based organization located in Richmond, Virginia. The records include administrative files, correspondence, newsletters, project files and photographs. Of interest are the project files that detail the Richmond Jaycees extensive charity work including such projects as the Special Olympic and Little Santa Christmas Party for underprivileged children, and public outreach programs such as helping the elderly and get out the vote campaigns. As well as community related projects such as the Richmond Christmas Parade and fundraising projects such as an annual Christmas tree sale.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is arranged into the following series:

scopecontent.p: This series consists of files related to the day to day running of the Richmond Jaycees, including minutes of board meetings, United States Jaycee handbooks and procedures, and the correspondence of several Richmond Jaycees presidents.

arrangement.p: The series is arranged alphabetically by folder title.

scopecontent.p: This series consists of newsletters created by the Richmond Jaycees to supply meeting and activities information to its membership. The newsletters have had several titles over the years. It first appeared as "As Jaycees See," then became "The Jaycees News Letter," before finally changing its name to "Jaybill."

This series consists of files created for the various projects conducted by the Richmond Jaycees. These projects range from the planning of meeting related to Jaycee membership to charity events, fundraising activities and community outreach. The Project files include descriptions of the project, budget, time line for implementation of the project, correspondence related to the project and often photographs taken during the project.
